1. Introduction
The moral theory of deontology, pioneered by Immanuel Kant, is a framework that attempts to draw the border between activities that are morally good and morally bad. This border is dictated by the categorical imperative, a simple test to judge the morality of all actions. The categorical imperative has multiple formulations, though one of the most common is: “Do only what can be accepted as universal law” (Kant). In other words, one should only consider an action to be moral if everyone can pursue the same action. We can use the categorical imperative to test the morality of a rule – formally referred to as a maxim – by simply checking if an impossibility or contradiction occurs if the maxim becomes universal (Kant). For example, the maxim “we are allowed to kill other people” will be judged invalid by the categorical imperative, because if everyone in the world had the freedom to murder anyone they want, society would quickly fall apart. This is very similar to a message that most people learn and internalize as children: “Treat others how you would like to be treated”. So, it is evident that the categorical imperative has at least some intuitive validity to it. However, upon closer examination, the categorical imperative reveals itself to be a poor guide to understanding our moral duties, due to its requirement for universality, no constraints on maxim specificity, and conflicting results.

2. The Universality Problem
One problem that the categorical imperative faces is that it tends to rule out maxims that are intuitively not immoral. Some actions are allowed to be done specifically because they are not universal, though the categorical imperative does not account for this. A simple example is the maxim: “One shall purchase a lot of bread on Sundays”. There is nothing intuitively immoral about someone choosing to live by this maxim. However, if we apply the categorical imperative, we have to accept that this maxim is only moral if everyone abided by it universally. If everyone in the world were to buy large amounts of bread from stores and bakeries, we would find ourselves in a severe bread shortage that would make it impossible for everyone to act in accordance with the maxim. We experience a contradiction; by forcing universality of this maxim, we find that it actually becomes impossible to follow. Of course, if everyone in the world were to purchase high quantities of bread on Sundays, we would run into logistical problems. But in the real world, this will not happen, and there are no worrisome consequences if just one person abides by the maxim. The categorical imperative fails to account for the fact that certain actions are moral because they are done in low amounts. Instead, the categorical imperative assumes that in order for a certain maxim to be moral, the world must have the capacity for everyone to follow it, which results in us having to rule out maxims that are intuitively not immoral.
In addition, the universality aspect of the categorical imperative attempts to establish values of fairness and impartiality by wrongfully assuming all humans to be equal and homogenous. For example, if we propose the maxim “One is allowed to capture and detain people who act disobedient”, we find that it is only moral for police officers to adhere to this maxim if everyone else also had the authority to do so. However, the point of law enforcement is to grant specific members of society special authority to help safeguard the interests of everyone else, and we find ourselves struggling to justify this partial treatment with the categorical imperative. A world where everyone exercised the same authority as police officers would quickly result in abuses of such power, and simple disagreements may result in violent altercations where two people attempt to injure and detain the other. The reason why the categorical imperative is faulty is because people are not all equal; individuals have different powers and roles in society. A safe, robust society relies on a flexible pool of citizens, but the categorical imperative severely limits us from granting privileges and power to some people over others. While this may help prevent evils like systemic oppression, it also prevents simple division of labor and law enforcement.

3. The Specificity Problem
	In addition to the problem of universality, the categorical imperative as stated by Kant also does not limit how specific a maxim can be. Let’s propose a reformed maxim of the police officer example above: “Only certified police officers have the authority to capture and detain those who act disobedient with the law”. Now, this maxim may pass the universality test. Baked into the maxim itself is a condition that applies only to a specific selection of people – police officers – meaning that everyone can now act in accordance with it while still generating the correct intention. Those that are not police officers will live life protected by those who are, and no contradiction arises. Notice, however, that we have now demonstrated a fatal flaw in the categorical imperative: it does not restrict how specific a maxim may be. Exploitations of this flaw can result in even further counterintuitive conclusions. We can add an arbitrary amount of conditional statements to a maxim, torturing it to work and be able to justify highly specific evils that result in no impossibility or contradiction. For example, we can also say that “Only certified police officers have the authority to capture and detain those who act disobedient with the law, or innocent people named Lebron James”. To my knowledge, only one additional person will be affected by including the last part of this maxim. While Lebron James may find himself constantly detained by police officers unlawfully, solely because of his name, the maxim generates no issues to anyone else once universalized. We now have to accept that it is moral for people named Lebron James to be detained simply for having the name Lebron James. We can extrapolate this further. One can imagine the horrific atrocities we are now able to justify as long as we construct a maxim that is highly specific and targeted towards some person or some group that is not associated with us. 

4. The Conflict Problem
	There is another problem with the categorical imperative, in that it can validate two maxims that directly oppose each other. For example, if we define maxim A as “Police officers can unlawfully detain people named Lebron James for no reason”, and maxim B as “Police officers cannot unlawfully detain people named Lebron James for no reason”, we find that we can universalize both without any issues. However, maxim A and maxim B are in direct opposition with each other. Kant wants us to do only in accordance with what can be universal law, but both A and B can become universal law, and we cannot adhere to both at the same time.
	This issue did not arise simply because I was being overly specific with my maxim. Consider the following maxims “One may eat dogs” and “One shall not eat dogs”. Once again, we can universalize directly opposing maxims without experiencing contradiction or impossibility in each independent case. Even when our maxims are quite general, we still come across conflicting results. The categorical imperative does not at all guide us in determining whether it is moral to eat dogs or not, so which moral code are we supposed to abide by? Deontology and the first formulation of the categorical imperative are not just flawed, they are unhelpful in guiding our moral code of conduct.

5. Conclusion
	To sum up, Kant’s first formulation of the categorical imperative is appealing at first glance due to the emphasis placed on fairness and equality, requiring people to consider whether their actions can be universalized. However, closer inspection reveals a multitude of problems. Firstly, requiring rules to be universalized in order to be moral violates many of our intuitive moral beliefs and requires such a degree of uniformity between people that is unfeasible to maintain in a society. Secondly, the categorical imperative provides no guideline on how specific a maxim can be, a flaw that can be exploited to justify any unjust action one can imagine. Lastly, the categorical imperative itself can give directly conflicting results concerning different moral problems, leaving us completely stranded in certain moral dilemmas.



Works Cited
Kant, Immanuel. Groundwork of the Metaphysics of Morals. 1785. 
